Executive Summary

The European Commission - Neighbourhood and Enlargement Negotiations is a major humanitarian donor, providing substantial yet variable funding—averaging around $19 million annually—with a focus on fewer, high-value disbursements rather than frequent smaller grants. Its geographic reach has expanded from 7 to 14 countries between 2022 and 2025, emphasizing growing regional diversification. Funding prioritization concentrates heavily on the global and Middle East regions, with notable fluctuations reflecting shifting strategic priorities. Compared to peers, the Commission exhibits distinct earmarking patterns, favoring targeted allocations aligned with neighborhood and enlargement contexts. Fundraising strategies should align with these dynamic regional focuses, accommodate large but intermittent funding flows, and tailor proposals to specific donor priorities for maximum impact.

Volatility

The funding data for the European Commission’s Neighbourhood and Enlargement Negotiations reveals a pattern of fewer but larger financial transactions compared to the top 10 other donors. Over the observed period from August 2023 to December 2025, there are 41 transactions with an average transaction amount of 4.9 million USD, while other donors average 2.9 million USD but conduct on average 371 transactions per year. This indicates that EC funding is characterized by higher-value but less frequent disbursements. The volatility is also reflected in a wide range of transaction values, with a minimum around 65 thousand USD and a maximum above 39 million USD. For humanitarian proposal writers, this suggests that the EC prefers substantial funding commitments at discrete intervals rather than continuous smaller contributions. This funding pattern may impact programming and planning by requiring more emphasis on managing large-scale projects with intermittent funding inflows. When designing proposals or evaluations, it is crucial to account for this irregular funding cadence and ensure readiness to absorb large funds efficiently, while advocating for more steady financial flows to improve program stability and impact continuity.
